all_steps.name: Melbourne
all_steps.description:
We arrived down under! Welcome to Melbourne Australia.

We are picking up a small camper van and going to road trip along the coast to Sydney.

Australia is a huge country, about the size of the continental US. However, its population is much less dense with 25 million people opposed to the 330 million in the US. 90 percent of the Australian population lives in just 0.22 per cent of the country’s land area and 87 percent live within 50 kilometres of the coast. More than two-thirds of Australians live in a capital city, with 40 percent of the population being in the two largest cities of Sydney and Melbourne.

Mainland Australia is the world’s largest island but the smallest continent. The country is divided into six states and two territories.

all_steps.name: Melbourne Museum
all_steps.description: We found ourselves at the Melbourne Museum. We went through a cool display about road safety.

all_steps.name: Hoiser Lane
all_steps.description:
One of the top sights to see in Melbourne is the Graffiti at Hoiser street. 

Although we didn’t spend much time in Melbourne, it seems like a really nice city. Artsy, clean, and great public transportation.

all_steps.name: Melbourne Australia Temple
all_steps.description:
The Melbourne Australia Temple was dedicated in 2000 by President Hinkley. It is currently undergoing renovations.

We stopped in the church and got some amazing advice for our trip from some senior missionaries.

all_steps.name: Nobbies Center
all_steps.description:
Philip Island is home to the largest population of Little Penguins (sometimes called fairy penguins or little blue penguins). Of the 18 penguin species around the world, little penguins are the smallest. They are small, about bowling pin size, with blue and white feathers.

While the adults were out at sea we were able to see some chicks in their nest!! Also the ocean views were very pretty!

all_steps.name: Philip Island Wildlife Park
all_steps.description:
At the wildlife park, we were able to see lots of Australia’s wildlife up close! We were even able to feed and pet the kangaroos and emus.

There were: 
Red kangaroos
Grey kangaroos 
Wallabies
Tiger Quoll
Emus
Koalas
Echidna 
Cassowary 
Blue Tongued Lizards 
And lots of birds!

(We weren’t able to see the dingos, Tasmanian Devil, or wombats).

all_steps.name: Walkerville - Promontory View
all_steps.description:
For our second night, we stayed in a caravan park right on the ocean. It was beautiful! We went on a bush walk up to an overlook of Waratah Bay. Along the trail we saw an echidna up close!!

In the class mammalia, there are three main groups: monotremes, marsupials, and placentals. The Order of Monotremes consist of four species of Echidnas and platypus — they lay eggs. Marsupials were the young are born young and finish development in the mothers pouch. Then the placentals are the most common mammals were the fetus is carried in the uterus until a late stage of development.

all_steps.name: Wilson’s Promontory National Park
all_steps.description:
At Wilson’s Prom we walked to a secluded beach. This was our first time swimming in the southern ocean! It is much cooler than the tropics!! But it was a really hot day, so it was nice to cool off! The water was perhaps the clearest we have seen!

We didn’t drive to the end of the peninsula at Wilson’s prom, but that is the southern most point of continental Australia.

all_steps.name: Eagle Point - Lakes Entrance
all_steps.description: Next night was at Lakes Entrance. There are so many cool birds in Australia!!

all_steps.name: Bairnsdale Branch
all_steps.description:
This morning we attended church at the Bairnsdale Branch. We were very grateful to be able to attend church, it has been a few weeks because there wasn’t a congregation accessible in Koh Lanta.

The branch was very small, especially because a few families were out on holiday. They were very grateful for visitors. Robbie passed the sacrament. Robbie, Fran, and Lindsay shared testimonies.

all_steps.name: Eden
all_steps.description: We stopped in the beautiful bay town of Eden. There we visited the killer whale museum. Whales frequent the bay here, especially in spring and fall as they migrate north from Antarctica. In the 1800’s whaling was popular in this bay. The whalers had a unique hunting situation with the Killer Whales where they would work together to hunt other whales such as the southern right whales, and humpback whales. The museum housed the skeleton of the well known ‘Old Thom’ killer whale.

all_steps.name: Mimosa Rocks National Park
all_steps.description: We arrived to our campsite and there waiting for us was a kangaroo! The first kangaroo we have seen in the wild! We saw many more as we took the short walk to the beach. The lighting at the beach was magical! And then we saw a possum when we were going to bed! Best place ever!!

all_steps.name: Happy Birthday Harvey!!
all_steps.description:
Harvey is 13! We have a teenager in the house!! (Or should I say campervan!)

To celebrate we hired surfboards in Tathra. The water was cold and the waves huge - a big difference than our surfing experience in Sri Lanka! Not sure if we will get used to this!!

The afternoon was drizzly (welcome reprieve from the heat wave) so we hung out at the park and got Pizza for diner.

Happy birthday Harvey!! We love you!!

all_steps.name: Bermagui
all_steps.description: We stopped at the Blue Pool in Bermagui for lunch. Beautiful coast here. We even saw 10+ seals hunting!

all_steps.name: Piper Lookout
all_steps.description: Quick stop and walk as we passed through Brown Mountain. Boy we have had temperature swings! 38 degrees to now 13!!

all_steps.name: Platypus in Bombala
all_steps.description: We took a small detour to a Platypus Nature Preserve. We didn’t see any at the reserve but kept looking when our caravan park was right on the river. We were in luck!! We saw a handful of platypuses!!! They are hard to photograph because they are so small and can hold their breath for 14 min!! But lots of ripples in the water and small glimpses. Here is a picture that someone else took in this part.

all_steps.name: 40 (yikes!) in Cooma
all_steps.description: I turned 40! Yikes! Robbie knitted this awesome hat. And the weather was perfect to wear it. We took it easy today, hung out at Flag park in Cooma played, ate cake, and made some new friends that helped us adjust our plans to get more out of Australia. We had a minimal bickering day (unfortunately rare this past week - van life is tough!!), so that was the best birthday present!

all_steps.name: Kosciuszko National Park
all_steps.description: Tonight we camped in Tom Groggin campground. We were surrounded by 100s of kangaroos!!! And had gorgeous views of Mount Kosciuszko, the tallest peak in Australia.

all_steps.name: Mount Kosciuszko
all_steps.description:
Today we hiked up to the summit of Mount Kosciuszko. Mount Kosciuszko is the tallest peak in Australia at 2,228 metres (7,310 ft). Depending on definitions of continents, it is on some Seven Summit lists.

We started our walk in Thredbo, a mini-mini Park City-ish ski town with summer mountain biking and activities (there were a ton of mountain bikers!!). We took the chairlift up about a third of the way, then hiked 13 km (8 miles) and 400 m (1.300 ft) elevation gain. The views were amazing! There were some nice nice alpine flowers as well. And a ton of ravens!!

all_steps.name: Cotter Campground
all_steps.description: It was rainy, so we had a movie night in the van. We watched Oddball - a great Australian film, highly recommend!
Canberra is the capital of Australia, similar to Washington DC. We decided to stop and see the parliament building.

all_steps.name: Bowral
all_steps.description: To break up our drive we stopped in this cute town at a patisserie. We got some treats and a meat pie! The meat pie I believe is an Aussie thing, and we liked it!

all_steps.name: Cooking on the Barbie
all_steps.description:
Just about all the campgrounds and parks have public use barbecue plates to use. So after watching others, we bought some meat and fired up the barbie!! 

Afterwards we walked along The Mystics beach near camp!

all_steps.name: Dapto Ward
all_steps.description: We attended church in the Dapto Ward today. It was lovely and the people were so friendly!

all_steps.name: Snorkeling at Bushrangers Bay Aquatic Reserve
all_steps.display_name: Snorkeling at Bushrangers Bay Aquatic Reserve
all_steps.description: We went snorkeling at Bushrangers Bay Aquatic Reserve. The water was a lot cooler than we have been used to lately, but we saw some cool fish!

all_steps.name: Surfing at the Farm
all_steps.description: We did some group surf lessons at the Farm today. The waves were calm and infrequent, and lots of students per instructor, so we had to exercise lots of patience. But it was a lot of fun!

all_steps.name: Beach Day in Wollongong
all_steps.description: Today we took it easy. Harvey slept in until 11, then we spent the day at the beach and hanging at our campground. We body surfed, then found a boggie board so gave that a go. We played cricket — cricket is a hugely popular sport here with it on TV and lots of pick up games in the parks and around the caravan parks. We did schoolwork, swam in the indoor pool, and played mini-golf!

all_steps.name: Sydney Australia Temple
all_steps.description: We visited the Sydney Australia Temple, the 28th dedicated temple. Robbie, Harvey and Lindsay did baptisms and Fran chatted with some Sisters in the waiting room. It was a great morning!

all_steps.name: Hi-top Campervan
all_steps.description: While we are grateful that our campervan provided a safe and reliable way to explore Australia, we are not sad to part ways. 2 weeks of the small space has more than tested all of our patience.  1,400 miles (2,200 km) later, we have returned the van. Our hotel tonight seems very luxurious!

all_steps.name: SeaLife Sydney
all_steps.description: While the boys returned the campervan, Fran and I walked to the Harbour and visited the aquarium. We especially enjoyed the dugong, sharks, rays, and penguins.

all_steps.name: Cinderella at the Sydney Opera House
all_steps.display_name: Cinderella at the Sydney Opera House
all_steps.description:
Tonight we went and saw the opera Cinderella at the iconic Sydney Opera House. If was so good and such a fun experience! 

During the interlude, we went into foyer and a huge lightning storm was taking place. It was quite dramatic! Needless to say our walk back to the hotel was quite wet. We've packed portable travel ponchos all over the world, but never seem to have them at the right time!

all_steps.name: Australian National Maritime Museum
all_steps.description: When researching things to do in Sydney, this made the very top of Harvey’s list. This muSEAum did not disappoint. We got to tour war ships, a submarine, and old spice trade ship. We saw some amazing ocean photography, and learned about deep sea exploration.

all_steps.name: Sydney
all_steps.description:
Sydney was a clean cosmopolitan city. It had a VERY different feel than the other parts of the country - didn’t feel like Australia. We really liked it. 

Our flight was delayed so we spent 5.5 hours at the airport! Jetstar is 0/2 for our flights so far.

all_steps.name: Cairns
all_steps.description: Between the hot weather and a late night the night before, we spent the day lounging at our hotel. We did homework, hung in the room, and tested out 3 of the resorts 4 pools.

all_steps.name: Daintree River cruise
all_steps.description: We went on a Daintree River cruise. We had lovely views of the river and mangroves. But it was too hot, even the crocs! We only saw a small glimpse of Bruce, a momma croc near her nest. It was still fun learning about the crocodiles and the ecology of the area.

all_steps.name: Daintree Rainforest National Park
all_steps.description:
It was so hot and muggy (85% humidity and 97 deg F), but a trip to Northern Queensland Australia would not be complete without visiting the Daintree Rainforest. The Daintree is the oldest rainforest in the world, over 180 million years old. It is a biodiversity hot spot and home to plants and animals endemic to the area. It has species that have been around since before the dinosaurs.

We visited the Discovery center that had board walks and interpretive signs. We sweated a lot!

all_steps.name: Cairns 1st Branch
all_steps.description: We went to church at the Cairns 1st branch. It was fantastic! The branch was quite large, two in Cairns. They were trying to get a stake formed and be a ward, but the requirements changed. We found some relatives, 11th cousins (thanks family history app), and will have dinner with them this evening.

all_steps.name: Diving the Great Barrier Reef
all_steps.description:
Today we went diving at the Great Barrier Reef! The Great Barrier Reef is the world's largest coral reef system, composed of over 2,900 individual reefs and 900 islands stretching for over 2,300 kilometres (1,400 mi) over an area of approximately 344,400 square kilometres (133,000 sq mi). 

We specifically dove at the Flynn Little Tracy and Milin Reef Three Sisters. We saw many beautiful fish, but the highlight was the many gorgeous corals. The most exciting marine life was 2 green sea turtles!

all_steps.name: Great Barrier Reef 2
all_steps.description:
We went diving a second day on the Great Barrier Reef. Robbie stayed behind because he was still so sea sick from the day before. Today we went to the Flynn Reef for two dives (Tracy and 2 Gordon’s) and the Moore Reef (Crevice).

The coral was gorgeous once again! We saw clown fish (Nemo), got to hang out with a Hawksbill Turtle, play with some sea cucumbers, moon jellies, about 30 baby cuddle fish, and a giant coral trout. Fran saw a small blacktip reef shark, but it swam off before the rest of us saw it.

all_steps.name: Josephine Falls
all_steps.description: Today we ventured out to see some waterfalls. The first one was a blast! The cool water (23 deg C) was refreshing!

all_steps.name: Millaa Millaa Waterfall
all_steps.description: Next we headed up to the Atherton Tablelands to the Millaa Millaa waterfall. Its 20m drop into the clear cool pool was fantastic! And we saw a turtle!

all_steps.name: Curtain Fig Tree
all_steps.description: This large fig tree in Curtain Fig Tree National Park is unique because the extensive aerial roots, that drop 15 metres to the forest floor, have formed a ‘curtain’. Starting from a seed dropped high in the canopy, this strangler fig grew vertical roots, which gradually became thicker and interwoven. Over hundreds of years these roots have strangled the host causing it to fall into a neighbouring tree-a stage unique to the development of this fig. Vertical fig roots then formed a curtain-like appearance and the host trees rotted away, leaving the freestanding fig tree. The tree is thought to be nearly 50 metres tall, with a trunk circumference of 39 metres, and is estimated to be over 500 years old.

all_steps.name: Lake Eacham
all_steps.description: Lake Eacham is a volcanic crater and was formed by massive explosions from the superheating of groundwater. Over time this crater has filled with water and created a lake that is 65m deep. The lake and the surrounding rainforest are now home to over 180 species of birds, schools of fish, and turtles. And even fresh water crocs and tree kangaroos. We only saw fish and biting flies.

all_steps.name: Cairns
all_steps.description: And we are off!!

all_steps.name: Melbourne Airport
all_steps.description: Another flight delay…. But it wasn’t bad hanging at the Melbourne airport. Decent lounge and then the airline gave us vouchers that we bought souvenirs with.

all_steps.name: New Zealand
all_steps.description: We have arrived! Took the long way, but we made it to New Zealand. Fran got momentarily detained at border control. We were going through the computer kiosk and we all got pass except for her. An agent took her to talk to the officer. She answered yes to the question “have you been to prison in the last 12 month.” Once they clarified that wasn’t actually true, she was through! 🤣 in her defense it was 3am.
